The article discusses the actions that the Administration has taken to improve access to mental health services. It highlights the fact that a significant number of American adults and children with mental illnesses do not receive the necessary treatment due to various barriers, such as cost and lack of awareness. The article mentions the funding secured for mental health initiatives, including training more professionals, helping educators recognize signs of mental health problems in young people, and supporting state-based approaches for high-risk individuals. It also discusses the expansion of insurance coverage for mental health services and the implementation of the Mental Health Parity and Addiction Equity Act. The article further mentions funding provided to Community Health Centers and rural areas to increase access to mental health services. The Administration's efforts to reduce negative attitudes and perceptions about mental illness and invest in research for new treatments are also highlighted.